6":"1170–1206","1175–1206":"1175–1206","1264":"1264","1175":"1175","1272":"1272","1194":"1194","1282":"1282","1170":"1170","1192":"1192","1206":"1206","1227":"1227","1249":"1249","1215":"1215","1237":"1237","1199":"1199","about 1227":"circa 1227","Bef 27 March 1249":"vóór 27 maart 1249","Stockport, Cheshire, England":"Stockport, Cheshire, England","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Denton, Lancashire, England":"Denton, Lancashire, England"},"en":{"1199–Bef 27 March 1249":"1199–before 27 March 1249","1192–1237":"1192–1237","1199–1249":"1199–1249","1215–1282":"1215–1282","1227–1264":"1227–1264","1227–1272":"1227–1272","1170–1206":"1170–1206","1175–1206":"1175–1206","1264":"1264","1175":"1175","1272":"1272","1194":"1194","1282":"1282","1170":"1170","1192":"1192","1206":"1206","1227":"1227","1249":"1249","1215":"1215","1237":"1237","1199":"1199","about 1227":"about 1227","Bef 27 March 1249":"before 27 March 1249","Stockport, Cheshire, England":"Stockport, Cheshire, England","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Denton, Lancashire, England":"Denton, Lancashire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Stockport","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Stopford  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Stopford","meanings":["English: locative name from Stockport (Cheshire), which is recorded as  <i>Stokeport</i> in 1188,  <i>Stockford</i> in 1283–8,  <i>Stopford</i> in 1347,  <i>Stoppord</i> in 1337, and  <i>Stapporte</i> in 1583."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Robert de Stockport was born in 1199, in Stockport, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Robert de Stockport, was 30 and his mother, Maud FitzRichard, was 24. He married Roese de Venables about 1227, in Denton, Lancashire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died before 27 March 1249, in Cheshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1199–Bef 27 March 1249":"1199–enne 27. märtsi 1249","1192–1237":"1192–1237","1199–1249":"1199–1249","1215–1282":"1215–1282","1227–1264":"1227–1264","1227–1272":"1227–1272","1170–1206":"1170–1206","1175–1206":"1175–1206","1264":"1264","1175":"1175","1272":"1272","1194":"1194","1282":"1282","1170":"1170","1192":"1192"